# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1903-chicago-white-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1902 Chicago White Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Sox had a record of 74–60, finishing in fourth place in the American League.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1903 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 33rd season of the franchise.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished sixth in the National League with a record of 58–80, 32 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1903 Brooklyn Superbas season** was a season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas began their slide from contention in the National League by finishing in fifth place.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] The **1903 Chicago Cubs season** was the 32nd season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 28th in the National League, and the 11th at West Side Park.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished third in the National League with a record of 82–56.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] On September 18, 1903, the Phillies' Chick Fraser pitched a no-hitter in the second game of a double header against the Cubs at West Side Park.
[src:1903-chicago-white-stockings-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] Fraser walked five batters, the Phillies committed four errors and won 10 to 0.
